07296nam a22007455i 9780773554337DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735543377 a10.1515/97807735543372doi  a(DE-B1597)657432  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJF799T782018 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a323/.04222300aTrust, Distrust, and Mistrust in Multinational Democracies :bComparative Perspectives /ced. by François Rocher, Dimitrios Karmis. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b10 figures, 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDemocracy, Diversity, and Citizen Engagement Series ;v400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tIntroduction: The Language of Trust, Distrust, and Mistrust in Multinational Democracies -- tTheoretical Debates -- tConceptions of Trust: From Social Mechanism to Normative Principle -- tDemocracy, Trust, and National Identity -- tTrust: The Key to the Progressive’s Dilemma between Solidarity and Diversity? -- tDemocratic Institutions and Representative Trust -- tVigilance, Trust, and “Fine Risks” in the Minefield of Multinational Democracies -- tThe Dynamics of Trust, Distrust, and Mistrust in Canada -- tThe Conditional Nature of Trust in Canada’s Multinational Constitutional Politics -- tThe Construction of Canada in Historical Perspective: Distrust as an Inherent Component of Constitutional Debates? -- tThe Delayed (and Qualified) Victory of the Meech Lake Accord:The Role of Constitutional Reform in Undermining and Restoring Intercommunal Trust -- tFederalism as Rejection of Nationalist Monisms -- tLinguistic Groups and Civil Society: Trust, Cooperation, and Accommodation in Canadian Voluntary Associations -- tComparative Perspectives -- tThrough the Mirror of Contingency: Trust and Mistrust in Multinational States -- tIdentity and Political Trust in Multinational Democracies: The Cases of Québec and Catalonia -- tTrust and Distrust in the Belgian Federation -- tTrust between Party Elites in Consociational Federations: The Case of Belgium -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe importance of research on the notion of trust has grown considerably in the social sciences over the last three decades. Much has been said about the decline of political trust in democracies and intense debates have occurred about the nature and complexity of the relationship between trust and democracy. Political trust is usually understood as trust in political institutions (including trust in political actors that inhabit the institutions), trust between citizens, and to a lesser extent, trust between groups. However, the literature on trust has given no special attention to the issue of trust between minority and majority nations in multinational democracies – countries that are not only multicultural but also constitutional associations containing two or more nations or peoples whose members claim to be self-governing and have the right of self-determination. This volume, part of the work of the Groupe de recherche sur les sociétés plurinationales (GRSP), is a comparative study of trust, distrust, and mistrust in multinational democracies, centring on Canada, Belgium, Spain, and the United Kingdom. Beliefs, attitudes, practices, and relations of trust, distrust, and mistrust are studied as situated, interacting, and coexisting phenomena that change over time and space. Contributors include Dario Castiglione (Exeter), Jérôme Couture (INRS-UCS), Kris Deschouwer (Vrije Universiteit Brussel), Jean Leclair (Montréal), Patti Tamara Lenard (Ottawa), Niels Morsink (Antwerp), Geneviève Nootens (Chicoutimi), Darren O’Toole (Ottawa), Alexandre Pelletier (Toronto), Réjean Pelletier (Laval), Philip Resnick (UBC), David Robichaud (Ottawa), Peter Russell (Toronto), Richard Simeon (Toronto), Dave Sinardet (Vrije Universiteit Brussel), and Jeremy Webber (Victoria).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aComparative government. 0aDemocracyxPublic opinionvCross-cultural studies. 0aPolitical alienationvCross-cultural studies. 0aPolitical participationvCross-cultural studies. 0aTrustxPolitical aspectsvCross-cultural studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh1 aCastiglione, Dario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarren, O’Toole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeschouwer, Kris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarmis, Dimitrios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarmis, Dimitrios, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeclair, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenard, Patti Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorsink, Niels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNootens, Geneviève, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPelletier, Alexandre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPelletier, Jérôme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPelletier, Réjean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aResnick, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobichaud, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRocher, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRocher, François, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRussell, P